WHY BOTH SSH AND HTTPS EXIST
GitHub allows two authentication methods:

ğŸ”µ 1. SSH = Key-based authentication
âœ” No password
 âœ” No token
 âœ” Stronger security
 âœ” Faster
 âœ” Once configured, never asks for login again
 âœ” Best for developers working daily in terminal
SSH uses:
git@github.com:username/repo.git

This matches your current working setup.

ğŸŸ¢ 2. HTTPS = Token-based authentication
âœ” Requires Personal Access Token (PAT)
 âœ” Works everywhere (even office networks, schools, companies)
 âœ” Easy for beginners
 âœ” Works without generating SSH keys
HTTPS uses:
https://github.com/username/repo.git


â­ THEN WHY HAVE BOTH IF PUSH IS SAME?
Because different situations need different methods.

ğŸ“ Reason 1 â€” Many companies block SSH
Some offices block port 22, which SSH needs.
 HTTPS (port 443) always works.
So corporate developers MUST use HTTPS.

ğŸ“ Reason 2 â€” Cloning public repos works anonymously via HTTPS
You can:
git clone https://github.com/.../repo.git

No login needed.

ğŸ“ Reason 3 â€” SSH is convenient for heavy developers
Daily contributors prefer SSH because:
Never asks password/token


More secure


Works better for automation



ğŸ“ Reason 4 â€” Some tools or scripts need HTTPS
CI/CD pipelines, servers, or cloud services often only support HTTPS tokens.

â­ Summary in One Line
HTTPS is simple & universal. SSH is secure & convenient.
 Both are allowed so that developers can choose what fits their environment.

â­ Which one should you use?
Since you already set up SSH successfully:
âœ” Use SSH for daily work (push/pull)
Super easy. No password required.
âœ” Use HTTPS only if:
SSH port is blocked


You want to use token-based access


Some system requires it


