FORKING WORKFLOW (VERY CLEAR VERSION)
Use this when you want to contribute to someone elseâ€™s repository.

â­ STEP 1 â€” Fork the Repo on GitHub
Open the original GitHub repo


Click Fork


Now the repo appears in your account:


github.com/YourUsername/ForkedRepo


â­ STEP 2 â€” Clone YOUR fork (not the original)
If using SSH:
git clone git@github.com:YourUsername/ForkedRepo.git
cd ForkedRepo

Or HTTPS:
git clone https://github.com/YourUsername/ForkedRepo.git
cd ForkedRepo


â­ STEP 3 â€” Add the ORIGINAL repo as â€œupstreamâ€
git remote add upstream git@github.com:OriginalUser/OriginalRepo.git

Check:
git remote -v

You should see:
origin    --> your fork
upstream  --> original repo

âœ” origin = your fork
 âœ” upstream = original repo

â­ STEP 4 â€” Create a Branch for Your Work
Never work on main.
 Always create a new branch:
git checkout -b feature-branch


â­ STEP 5 â€” Make Changes and Commit
git add .
git commit -m "Added new feature"


â­ STEP 6 â€” Push Branch to YOUR Fork
git push -u origin feature-branch


â­ STEP 7 â€” Create a Pull Request (PR)
Go to:
github.com/YourUsername/ForkedRepo

You will see:
Compare & Pull Request

Click â†’ Write description â†’ Submit PR.

â­ STEP 8 â€” KEEP YOUR FORK UPDATED
When the original repo gets new updates, sync them to your fork.
Step A: Fetch original repo updates
git fetch upstream

Step B: Update your main branch
git checkout main
git merge upstream/main

OR easier:
git pull upstream main

Step C: Push updated main to your GitHub fork
git push origin main

