CLEAR SUMMARY OF IMPORTANT COMMANDS
LOCAL
git init       â†’ start repo on your PC
git add .      â†’ stage files on your PC
git commit     â†’ save on your PC
git push       â†’ send from PC â†’ GitHub (remote)

REMOTE
git remote add origin <url>  â†’ link PC repo â†’ GitHub repo
git remote add upstream <url>â†’ link PC repo â†’ original repo (in forking)
git remote -v                â†’ show GitHub connections
git remote set-url origin    â†’ change GitHub link


Branching
git branch
git checkout -b new-branch
git checkout main
git merge new-branch

Updating your fork
git pull upstream main


WHAT IS A MERGE CONFLICT?
A merge conflict happens when Git cannot automatically merge changes because:
two people changed the same line


or one edited a file while the other deleted it


or commits overlap



âœ… GENERAL PROCESS TO SOLVE ANY CONFLICT
Git warns you about a conflict
Open the conflicted file â†’ you will see:


<<<<<<< HEAD
(your changes)
=======
(their changes)
>>>>>>> branch-name

Decide what to keep:


your version


their version


combine both


manually edit


Remove the conflict markers:
 <<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>>


Save the file


Run:


git add <file>
git commit -m "Resolved conflict"
git push



















HTTPS

âœ… STEP 1 â€” Check HTTPS Remote
To see current URL:
git remote -v

If you see SSH like:
git@github.com:ShubhamDudhbhate-VJTI/OST.git

â†’ Thatâ€™s SSH.
To switch to HTTPS:
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/ShubhamDudhbhate-VJTI/OST.git

Done.

âœ… STEP 2 â€” Generate a Personal Access Token (PAT)
PAT replaces your password.
Go to GitHub:
âš™ï¸ Settings â†’ Developer Settings â†’ Personal Access Tokens
 Choose:
Fine-grained token (recommended)
Permissions needed:
âœ” Contents â†’ Read and Write
 âœ” Pull Requests â†’ Read and Write
 âœ” Metadata â†’ Read
Generate â†’ Copy the token.
 (You cannot see it again later.)

â— IMPORTANT
When Git asks:
Username for 'https://github.com':

You enter:
Your GitHub username (ShubhamDudhbhate)

Then it asks:
Password for â€œâ€

You MUST paste your PAT (token)
 NOT your GitHub password.

âœ… STEP 3 â€” Test push using HTTPS
git push -u origin main

It will ask:
âœ” Username â†’ your GitHub username
 âœ” Password â†’ your PAT token
If correct â†’ push works.

ğŸŒŸ AFTER YOU LOGIN ONCE
Git will remember your PAT using Windows Credential Manager.
You wonâ€™t need to enter it again.

â­ SUMMARY OF HTTPS SETUP COMMANDS
Set HTTPS remote:
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/YourUser/YourRepo.git

Clone using HTTPS:
git clone https://github.com/YourUser/YourRepo.git

Push using HTTPS:
git push -u origin main

Git will ask for username + PAT.



METHOD 1 â€” Use Credential Manager (BEST for Windows)
Git can save your token permanently using:
Run this in WSL:
git config --global credential.helper manager-core

This uses Git Credential Manager (GCM) which securely stores your PAT in Windows Credential Manager.
Now push:
git push -u origin main

It will ask:
âœ” Username â†’ your GitHub username
 âœ” Password â†’ your PAT token
Then GCM stores it forever.
 Next time â†’ no password asked.

 IF YOU PREVIOUSLY UNSET CREDENTIALS
Run this to clean old settings:
git config --global --unset credential.helper
git config --system --unset credential.helper 2>/dev/null
git config --local --unset credential.helper 2>/dev/null

Then set again:
git config --global credential.helper manager-core

