Summery:

âœ… 1. SIMILARITIES (commands that are 100% SAME)
Whether you use SSH or HTTPS, the following commands NEVER change:
âœ” Git Basics (same)
git init
git add .
git commit -m "msg"
git status
git log

âœ” Branch commands (same)
git branch
git checkout -b feature
git checkout main
git merge feature

âœ” Local operations (same)
Everything done inside your PC is 100% same for SSH & HTTPS.

ğŸš€ 2. PUSH / PULL commands (same)
git push
git push -u origin main
git pull
git fetch

Even here â€” SSH or HTTPS makes NO difference.

ğŸ”¥ 3. WHAT IS DIFFERENT? Only ONE thing: the remote URL
SSH remote URL looks like:
git@github.com:Username/Repo.git

HTTPS remote URL looks like:
https://github.com/Username/Repo.git

Thatâ€™s the ONLY difference in commands.

ğŸ”¥ 4. COMMANDS THAT ARE DIFFERENT
A) Add remote
SSH:
git remote add origin git@github.com:Username/Repo.git

HTTPS:
git remote add origin https://github.com/Username/Repo.git

B) Change remote
SSH:
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:Username/Repo.git

HTTPS:
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/Username/Repo.git

C) Authentication required?
SSH:
 âœ”ï¸ No password
 âœ”ï¸ No token
 âœ”ï¸ Never asks again
HTTPS:
 âŒ Cannot use password
 âœ”ï¸ Must use Personal Access Token (PAT)
 ğŸ” If no credential helper â†’ asks again

ğŸ§  5. Authentication difference (VERY IMPORTANT)
SSH Login Test
ssh -T git@github.com

If SSH keys are set â†’ login works.
HTTPS Login Uses PAT
git push

Then it asks:
Username (GitHub username)


Password â†’ use PAT, not GitHub password



ğŸ§© 6. When cloning â€” difference
SSH:
git clone git@github.com:Username/Repo.git

HTTPS:
git clone https://github.com/Username/Repo.git






